snippet.textDisplay: If I remember rightly, a recent Mane headed goal was erased as he was offside by an armpit. It is clear the rules are being administered fairly as most teams have suffered due to the strictness of the rule interpretations; however it is the spirit of the game that is being damaged. Maybe we'll see some tweaks for next season - possibly offside only being called if an attacking players FEET are ahead of all defensive players, as opposed to any part of the body. They need to do something - we're now seeing two celebrations for a goal; one when the ball hits the back of the net; and then another several minutes later when VAR agrees it's a goal. Flip the coin and you see celebrations turn to recrimination when VAR disallows it. Is that teally what the Premier League wants???? 😐

snippet.textDisplay: As the rules are currently written, it’s offsides, but the rule needs to be changed. Between the rule and the misuse of VAR as it was intended, situations like this are so frustrating, even when they benefit my team (Liverpool), which is exactly what happened today. Wolves come off a wild comeback against Manchester City and should have tied with Liverpool a couple of days later, although who knows how the second half goes with it being level again going into halftime. Whatever happens, Wolves and their fans should be mad that this is what they have to live with after playing so well recently.

snippet.textDisplay: This is a result of small, but very high profile, mistakes by human referees. Those mistakes had the media screaming for the introduction of VAR. Now we've got it and they hate it. If VAR is supposed to be for "clear and obvious" errors by the referee, how do you determine the degree of clear and obvious? Millimeters? Inches? In my mind, if you need to even start using that measuring tool then it was not a clear and obvious error. I think lots of people thought that VAR was going to solve every controversial decision that referees made. The ironic part is that, big picture, nothing has really changed. The good teams are still good and the bad teams are still bad, and the results and the table reflect that.
